subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/references
object: A related resource that is referenced, cited, or otherwise pointed to by the described resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/dateCopyrighted
object: Date of copyright of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/audience
object: A class of agents for whom the resource is intended or useful.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/RFC3066
object: RFC 3066 has been obsoleted by RFC 4646.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/educationLevel
object: A class of agents, defined in terms of progression through an educational or training context, for which the described resource is intended.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/UDC
object: The set of conceptual resources specified by the Universal Decimal Classification.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/license
object: Recommended practice is to identify the license document with a URI. If this is not possible or feasible, a literal value that identifies the license may be provided.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/hasVersion
object: A related resource that is a version, edition, or adaptation of the described resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/LocationPeriodOrJurisdiction
object: A location, period of time, or jurisdiction.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/relation
object: Recommended practice is to identify the related resource by means of a URI.  If this is not possible or feasible, a string conforming to a formal identification system may be provided.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/identifier
object: Recommended practice is to identify the resource by means of a string conforming to an identification system. Examples include International Standard Book Number (ISBN), Digital Object Identifier (DOI), and Uniform Resource Name (URN).  Persistent identifiers should be provided as HTTP URIs.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isReferencedBy
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of References.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/rightsHolder
object: Recommended practice is to refer to the rights holder with a URI. If this is not possible or feasible, a literal value that identifies the rights holder may be provided.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/Point
object: The set of points in space defined by their geographic coordinates according to the DCMI Point Encoding Scheme.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/creator
object: Recommended practice is to identify the creator with a URI.  If this is not possible or feasible, a literal value that identifies the creator may be provided.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isRequiredBy
object: A related resource that requires the described resource to support its function, delivery, or coherence.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/LCC
object: The set of conceptual resources specified by the Library of Congress Classification.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/PeriodOfTime
object: An interval of time that is named or defined by its start and end dates.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/format
object: The file format, physical medium, or dimensions of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/rights
object: Information about rights held in and over the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/Period
object: The set of time intervals defined by their limits according to the DCMI Period Encoding Scheme.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/LCSH
object: The set of labeled concepts specified by the Library of Congress Subject Headings.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/issued
object: Recommended practice is to describe the date, date/time, or period of time as recommended for the property Date, of which this is a subproperty.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/Frequency
object: A rate at which something recurs.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/hasFormat
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Is Format Of.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/hasVersion
object: Changes in version imply substantive changes in content rather than differences in format. This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Is Version Of.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/Box
object: The set of regions in space defined by their geographic coordinates according to the DCMI Box Encoding Scheme.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/issued
object: Date of formal issuance of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/requires
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Is Required By.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/LinguisticSystem
object: Written, spoken, sign, and computer languages are linguistic systems.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isFormatOf
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Has Format.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/extent
object: The size or duration of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/RightsStatement
object: A statement about the intellectual property rights (IPR) held in or over a resource, a legal document giving official permission to do something with a resource, or a statement about access rights.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/description
object: Description may include but is not limited to: an abstract, a table of contents, a graphical representation, or a free-text account of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/mediator
object: An entity that mediates access to the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/valid
object: Recommended practice is to describe the date, date/time, or period of time as recommended for the property Date, of which this is a subproperty.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/created
object: Date of creation of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/publisher
object: An entity responsible for making the resource available.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/available
object: Date that the resource became or will become available.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/TGN
object: The set of places specified by the Getty Thesaurus of Geographic Names.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/provenance
object: A statement of any changes in ownership and custody of the resource since its creation that are significant for its authenticity, integrity, and interpretation.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/dateSubmitted
object: Date of submission of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/NLM
object: The set of conceptual resources specified by the National Library of Medicine Classification.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/requires
object: A related resource that is required by the described resource to support its function, delivery, or coherence.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/MethodOfAccrual
object: A method by which resources are added to a collection.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isPartOf
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Has Part.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/Jurisdiction
object: The extent or range of judicial, law enforcement, or other authority.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/available
object: Recommended practice is to describe the date, date/time, or period of time as recommended for the property Date, of which this is a subproperty.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/coverage
object: Spatial topic and spatial applicability may be a named place or a location specified by its geographic coordinates. Temporal topic may be a named period, date, or date range. A jurisdiction may be a named administrative entity or a geographic place to which the resource applies. Recommended practice is to use a controlled vocabulary such as the Getty Thesaurus of Geographic Names [[TGN](https://www.getty.edu/research/tools/vocabulary/tgn/index.html)]. Where appropriate, named places or time periods may be used in preference to numeric identifiers such as sets of coordinates or date ranges.  Because coverage is so broadly defined, it is preferable to use the more specific subproperties Temporal Coverage and Spatial Coverage.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accrualMethod
object: Recommended practice is to use a value from the Collection Description Accrual Method Vocabulary [[DCMI-ACCRUALMETHOD](https://dublincore.org/groups/collections/accrual-method/)].

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/URI
object: The set of identifiers constructed according to the generic syntax for Uniform Resource Identifiers as specified by the Internet Engineering Task Force.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/hasPart
object: A related resource that is included either physically or logically in the described resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isVersionOf
object: A related resource of which the described resource is a version, edition, or adaptation.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/DDC
object: The set of conceptual resources specified by the Dewey Decimal Classification.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isVersionOf
object: Changes in version imply substantive changes in content rather than differences in format. This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Has Version.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCitation
object: Recommended practice is to include sufficient bibliographic detail to identify the resource as unambiguously as possible.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/modified
object: Recommended practice is to describe the date, date/time, or period of time as recommended for the property Date, of which this is a subproperty.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/dateAccepted
object: Recommended practice is to describe the date, date/time, or period of time as recommended for the property Date, of which this is a subproperty.  Examples of resources to which a date of acceptance may be relevant are a thesis (accepted by a university department) or an article (accepted by a journal).

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accrualPeriodicity
object: The frequency with which items are added to a collection.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isPartOf
object: A related resource in which the described resource is physically or logically included.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/RFC1766
object: The set of tags, constructed according to RFC 1766, for the identification of languages.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/extent
object: Recommended practice is to specify the file size in megabytes and duration in ISO 8601 format.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/DCMIType
object: The set of classes specified by the DCMI Type Vocabulary, used to categorize the nature or genre of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accessRights
object: Access Rights may include information regarding access or restrictions based on privacy, security, or other policies.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accrualPeriodicity
object: Recommended practice is to use a value from the Collection Description Frequency Vocabulary [[DCMI-COLLFREQ](https://dublincore.org/groups/collections/frequency/)].

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/type
object: Recommended practice is to use a controlled vocabulary such as the DCMI Type Vocabulary [[DCMI-TYPE](http://dublincore.org/documents/dcmi-type-vocabulary/)]. To describe the file format, physical medium, or dimensions of the resource, use the property Format.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/IMT
object: The set of media types specified by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/Agent
object: A resource that acts or has the power to act.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/dateSubmitted
object: Recommended practice is to describe the date, date/time, or period of time as recommended for the property Date, of which this is a subproperty.  Examples of resources to which a 'Date Submitted' may be relevant include a thesis (submitted to a university department) or an article (submitted to a journal).

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/RFC3066
object: The set of tags constructed according to RFC 3066 for the identification of languages.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/contributor
object: An entity responsible for making contributions to the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/Policy
object: A plan or course of action by an authority, intended to influence and determine decisions, actions, and other matters.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isReferencedBy
object: A related resource that references, cites, or otherwise points to the described resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/RFC4646
object: The set of tags constructed according to RFC 4646 for the identification of languages.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/title
object: A name given to the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/dateCopyrighted
object: Typically a year.  Recommended practice is to describe the date, date/time, or period of time as recommended for the property Date, of which this is a subproperty.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/instructionalMethod
object: A process, used to engender knowledge, attitudes and skills, that the described resource is designed to support.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/hasPart
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Is Part Of.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/ISO639-3
object: The set of three-letter codes listed in ISO 639-3 for the representation of names of languages.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isFormatOf
object: A pre-existing related resource that is substantially the same as the described resource, but in another format.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/language
object: Recommended practice is to use either a non-literal value representing a language from a controlled vocabulary such as ISO 639-2 or ISO 639-3, or a literal value consisting of an IETF Best Current Practice 47 [[IETF-BCP47](https://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47)] language tag.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/Location
object: A spatial region or named place.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/format
object: Recommended practice is to use a controlled vocabulary where available. For example, for file formats one could use the list of Internet Media Types [[MIME](https://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml)].  Examples of dimensions include size and duration.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/provenance
object: The statement may include a description of any changes successive custodians made to the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/LinguisticSystem
object: A system of signs, symbols, sounds, gestures, or rules used in communication.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/PhysicalMedium
object: Examples include paper, canvas, or DVD.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/replaces
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Is Replaced By.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/LicenseDocument
object: A legal document giving official permission to do something with a resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/replaces
object: A related resource that is supplanted, displaced, or superseded by the described resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/medium
object: The material or physical carrier of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/tableOfContents
object: A list of subunits of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/SizeOrDuration
object: A dimension or extent, or a time taken to play or execute.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/hasFormat
object: A related resource that is substantially the same as the pre-existing described resource, but in another format.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/rightsHolder
object: A person or organization owning or managing rights over the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accessRights
object: Information about who access the resource or an indication of its security status.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/contributor
object: The guidelines for using names of persons or organizations as creators apply to contributors.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/license
object: A legal document giving official permission to do something with the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isReplacedBy
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Replaces.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/subject
object: Recommended practice is to refer to the subject with a URI. If this is not possible or feasible, a literal value that identifies the subject may be provided. Both should preferably refer to a subject in a controlled vocabulary.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/rights
object: Typically, rights information includes a statement about various property rights associated with the resource, including intellectual property rights.  Recommended practice is to refer to a rights statement with a URI.  If this is not possible or feasible, a literal value (name, label, or short text) may be provided.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/source
object: A related resource from which the described resource is derived.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/coverage
object: The spatial or temporal topic of the resource, spatial applicability of the resource, or jurisdiction under which the resource is relevant.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accrualPolicy
object: Recommended practice is to use a value from the Collection Description Accrual Policy Vocabulary [[DCMI-ACCRUALPOLICY](https://dublincore.org/groups/collections/accrual-policy/)].

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accrualPolicy
object: The policy governing the addition of items to a collection.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/creator
object: An entity responsible for making the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/valid
object: Date (often a range) of validity of a resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/ISO3166
object: The set of codes listed in ISO 3166-1 for the representation of names of countries.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isRequiredBy
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Requires.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/alternative
object: The distinction between titles and alternative titles is application-specific.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/references
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. This property is an inverse property of Is Referenced By.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/isReplacedBy
object: A related resource that supplants, displaces, or supersedes the described resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/audience
object: Recommended practice is to use this property with non-literal values from a vocabulary of audience types.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/BibliographicResource
object: A book, article, or other documentary resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/date
object: A point or period of time associated with an event in the lifecycle of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/MethodOfInstruction
object: A process that is used to engender knowledge, attitudes, and skills.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/RFC5646
object: The set of tags constructed according to RFC 5646 for the identification of languages.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/accrualMethod
object: The method by which items are added to a collection.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/SizeOrDuration
object: Examples include a number of pages, a specification of length, width, and breadth, or a period in hours, minutes, and seconds.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/dateAccepted
object: Date of acceptance of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/ISO639-2
object: The three-letter alphabetic codes listed in ISO639-2 for the representation of names of languages.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/type
object: The nature or genre of the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/alternative
object: An alternative name for the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/instructionalMethod
object: Instructional Method typically includes ways of presenting instructional materials or conducting instructional activities, patterns of learner-to-learner and learner-to-instructor interactions, and mechanisms by which group and individual levels of learning are measured.  Instructional methods include all aspects of the instruction and learning processes from planning and implementation through evaluation and feedback.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/mediator
object: In an educational context, a mediator might be a parent, teacher, teaching assistant, or care-giver.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/MESH
object: The set of labeled concepts specified by the Medical Subject Headings.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/created
object: Recommended practice is to describe the date, date/time, or period of time as recommended for the property Date, of which this is a subproperty.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/modified
object: Date on which the resource was changed.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCitation
object: A bibliographic reference for the resource.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/conformsTo
object: An established standard to which the described resource conforms.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/ProvenanceStatement
object: Any changes in ownership and custody of a resource since its creation that are significant for its authenticity, integrity, and interpretation.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/date
object: Date may be used to express temporal information at any level of granularity.  Recommended practice is to express the date, date/time, or period of time according to ISO 8601-1 [[ISO 8601-1](https://www.iso.org/iso-8601-date-and-time-format.html)] or a published profile of the ISO standard, such as the W3C Note on Date and Time Formats [[W3CDTF](https://www.w3.org/TR/NOTE-datetime)] or the Extended Date/Time Format Specification [[EDTF](http://www.loc.gov/standards/datetime/)].  If the full date is unknown, month and year (YYYY-MM) or just year (YYYY) may be used. Date ranges may be specified using ISO 8601 period of time specification in which start and end dates are separated by a '/' (slash) character.  Either the start or end date may be missing.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/Standard
object: A reference point against which other things can be evaluated or compared.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/MediaType
object: A file format or physical medium.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/W3CDTF
object: The set of dates and times constructed according to the W3C Date and Time Formats Specification.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/source
object: This property is intended to be used with non-literal values. The described resource may be derived from the related resource in whole or in part. Best practice is to identify the related resource by means of a URI or a string conforming to a formal identification system.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/identifier
object: An unambiguous reference to the resource within a given context.
